#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:1
#. TRANSLATORS: Lesson header
msgid "Time Delta"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:5
msgid "We've seen how we can use our character's [code]_process()[/code] function to make it move continuously."
msgstr "우리는 캐릭터의 [code]_process()[/code] 함수를 사용하여 캐릭터가 계속해서 움직이도록 할 수 있는 방법을 보았습니다."

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:17
#, fuzzy
msgid "But it's not just our character that has a [code]_process()[/code] function. Almost everything in the game has a [code]_process()[/code] function!"
msgstr "하지만 [code]_process()[/code] 함수는 우리 캐릭터만 가지고 있는 것이 아닙니다. 게임 내 거의 모든 것이 [code]_process()[/code] 함수를 가지고 있습니다!"

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:18
msgid "Dozens of times per second, Godot runs every [code]_process()[/code] function in the game to update the game world."
msgstr "초당 수십 번씩, Godot은 게임 내 모든 [code]_process()[/code] 함수를 실행하여 게임 세계를 업데이트합니다."

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:19
msgid "After that, it displays an image of the game world on the screen. We call that image a [b]frame[/b]."
msgstr "그 후, 게임 세계의 이미지를 화면에 표시합니다. 이 이미지를 [b]프레임[/b]이라고 부릅니다."

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:20
msgid "Godot then moves on to calculating the next frame."
msgstr "Godot은 다음 프레임을 계산하는 작업으로 넘어갑니다."

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:21
msgid "As this happens dozens of times per second, you get the illusion of movement. This is similar to how traditional animation works."
msgstr "이 과정이 초당 수십 번씩 반복되면서, 움직임의 환상을 얻게 됩니다. 이는 전통적인 애니메이션이 작동하는 방식과 유사합니다."

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:17
#. TRANSLATORS: Note title
msgid "This sounds like Frames Per Second..."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:18
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "You may have heard of frames per second, or FPS for short. Games often run at 60 frames per second."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:19
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "It means that everything in the game updates 60 times each second."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:20
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "The number varies while playing, depending on the game and the device it runs on."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:21
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "On powerful computers, you may get frame rates in the hundreds or thousands of frames per second."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:29
msgid "Let's look at the [code]_process()[/code] function in more detail."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:29
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz question
msgid "What parameter does the _process() function take?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:29
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "The [code]_process()[/code] function has one parameter named [code]delta[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:29
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "rotate"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:29
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "delta"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:40
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Frames take varying amounts of time to calculate"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:56
msgid "Depending on the game, the computer, and what the game engine needs to calculate, frames take more or less time to display."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:57
msgid "There will always be small variations from frame to frame."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:58
msgid "That is why the [code]_process()[/code] function receives a [code]delta[/code] parameter."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:59
msgid "Delta represents a time difference. It's the time it took Godot to complete the previous frame, in seconds."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:60
msgid "We can use it to make sure the game runs at the same speed on all computers."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:61
msgid "This is because different computers have different processing power, so a fast computer will have more frames per second than a slow computer."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:62
msgid "If we ignore [code]delta[/code], movement speed will vary depending on the computer. Delta helps to make the game consistent for everyone."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:56
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz question
msgid "What do we know about delta?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:56
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "[code]delta[/code] is the time it took Godot to complete the previous frame in seconds."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:56
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "It's very small because frames happen many times a second."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:56
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "It varies each frame because Godot has more or less to process each frame."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:56
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "It's a value in seconds."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:56
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "It varies each frame."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:56
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "It's the time it took Godot to complete the previous frame."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:67
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Multiplying by delta"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:73
msgid "The [code]delta[/code] you get in [code]_process()[/code] is a time difference in seconds. It will generally be a tiny decimal number."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:74
msgid "To apply [code]delta[/code], you need to [i]multiply[/i] your speed values by it."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:79
msgid "When multiplying by [code]delta[/code], you make motion [i]time-dependent[/i] rather than [i]frame-dependent[/i]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:80
msgid "That's essential to make your game consistent and fair."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:79
#. TRANSLATORS: Note title
msgid "Why do we use the number 3.0 in this example?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:80
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
#. The "term" in [glossary term="<term>"] should NOT be translated here
msgid "At the top of the lesson, we made the robot rotate a fixed amount every frame: [code]0.05[/code] [glossary term=\"radians\"]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:81
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "In the example above, we now [i]multiply[/i] the argument by the very small [code]delta[/code] value, a value much smaller than [code]1.0[/code]. It makes the robot turn at a constant speed over time."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:82
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "However, multiplying by a number below [code]1.0[/code] like [code]delta[/code] makes the result smaller."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:83
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "To compensate for that and make the robot turn fast enough, we use a larger number than before, [code]3.0[/code] instead of [code]0.05[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:84
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "Those numbers have two different [i]units[/i]: [code]0.05[/code] is an [i]angle[/i] in radians, while [code]3.0[/code] is an [i]angular speed[/i] in radians per second."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:85
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "When you multiply an angular speed by a time delta, it gives you an angle."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:86
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "Don't worry if it's a little confusing for now. It'll eventually click as you deal with speed, acceleration, and motion in your game projects."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:95
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Why the time between frames matters"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:107
msgid "The time it takes to display a new frame varies."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:108
msgid "If you don't take that time into account in your code, your game will have gameplay issues and bugs. Godot provides that time to the [code]_process()[/code] function through the [code]delta[/code] parameter."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:109
msgid "In the example below, the top robot moves using [code]delta[/code]. As a result, it moves at a fixed speed."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:110
msgid "The bottom robot moves over a constant distance every frame, [i]without[/i] taking [code]delta[/code] into account. It will move faster or slower than the top robot on [i]your[/i] computer."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:111
msgid "The bottom robot will move [i]differently for everyone[/i]!"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:115
msgid "Multiplying time-sensitive values by [code]delta[/code] makes them [b]time-dependent[/b] rather than [b]frame-dependent[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:116
msgid "Thanks to that, we get reliable movement over time."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:117
msgid "Frame times vary from computer to computer and from frame to frame during gameplay. Because frame times vary, if [code]delta[/code] is not used, movement speed will differ for each player, making the game inconsistent and messy."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:115
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz question
msgid "What does this mean?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:115
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "The [code]*[/code] symbol means we're multiplying [code]rotation_speed[/code] by [code]delta[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:115
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "We're multiplying rotation_speed by delta."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:115
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "We're dividing delta by rotation_speed."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:115
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "We're adding rotation_speed to delta."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:115
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "We're subtracting delta from rotation_speed."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:126
msgid "In the next practice, we'll use delta to make the rotation time-dependent."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:126
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Rotating Using Delta"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:126
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "At the moment, the rotation of the robot is frame-dependent."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:126
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Add [code]delta[/code] to make the rotational speed time-dependent."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:126
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "The robot should rotate [code]2[/code] radians per second."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:126
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Multiply the radians by [code]delta[/code]"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:146
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Moving in a Circle Using Delta"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:146
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "In this practice, make the robot move in a smooth circle using delta."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:146
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "The robot should rotate [code]2[/code] radians per second and move [code]100[/code] pixels per second forward. This combination makes it travel in a clockwise circle."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:146
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "[b]Note:[/b] Please write the values in the parentheses when calling the functions. If you define extra variables, we will not be able to check your practice."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-11-time-delta/lesson.bbcode:146
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Make sure to multiply each parameter by [code]delta[/code]"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:1
#. TRANSLATORS: Lesson header
msgid "Using Variables to Make Code Easier to Read"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:7
msgid "In this lesson, we'll make our code easier to follow and understand at a glance."
msgstr "이 단원에서는 코드를 한 눈에 쉽게 따라하고 이해할 수 있도록 만들겠습니다."

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:8
msgid "Take a look at this example."
msgstr "이 예제를 살펴보세요."

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:9
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz question
msgid "In the above example, what does the number 4 mean?"
msgstr "위 예시에서 숫자 4는 무엇을 의미하나요?"

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:9
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "The code above rotates the character [code]4[/code] radians per second."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:9
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "It's how fast the character rotates."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:9
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "It's how far the character moves in pixels."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:9
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "It's how long the rotation takes."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:20
msgid "We can guess what a number represents by looking at the function names, but it's harder to recall what this number does by quickly looking at the code."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:21
msgid "We've seen how different functions have their own names. Using these names communicates to developers what the functions do."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:30
msgid "As we learned in lesson 8, we can also assign labels to numbers to help us remember what they do."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:31
msgid "We call these labels [i]variables[/i]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:32
msgid "[b]A variable is a label for a value we can save, change, and read later.[/b]"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:33
msgid "Let's recap how to define a variable."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:34
msgid "We improve the first example to make it clear what the number [code]4[/code] does."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:38
msgid "Labeling a value makes the code easier for us to read now [i]and[/i] in the future."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:38
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz question
msgid "In the above example, which line defines the angular speed variable?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:38
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "We create the [code]angular_speed[/code] variable, then assign it the value of [code]4[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:38
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "var angular_speed = 4"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:38
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "func _process(delta):"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:38
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "rotate(angular_speed * delta)"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:51
msgid "If we define variables outside of functions, we can re-use them in different functions."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:52
msgid "Because any function can use variables we define outside of them, we call these variables [b]script-wide[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:53
msgid "Here we use the [code]angular_speed[/code] script-wide variable in both the [code]_process()[/code] function and the [code]set_angular_speed()[/code] function."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:59
msgid "We can also define variables inside of functions."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:60
msgid "We align the variable assignment by indenting to make it part of the function body. Make sure to create the variable before using it!"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:61
#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:69
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "If we define a variable inside of a function, only that function can use it."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:67
msgid "The [code]angular_speed[/code] variable only exists inside [code]_process()[/code], because we defined it there. The [code]set_angular_speed()[/code] function can't use it."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:68
msgid "Trying to use it there will result in an error."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:69
msgid "Here's what this error might look like."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:69
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz question
msgid "Where can we define variables?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:69
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "Functions can use any variables defined outside of functions. These variables are [b]script-wide[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:69
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "Outside of functions."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:69
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "Inside of functions."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:81
msgid "Variables are also great at grouping values that control how a character behaves."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:82
msgid "Grouping them in this way allows us to easily change them."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:85
msgid "In the following practices, we'll define variables and use them with some familiar functions to make our code more readable."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:85
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Clarifying Code Using Variables"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:85
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Let's give the [code]4[/code] here a label so we know what it does."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:85
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Create a variable called [code]angular_speed[/code] outside of the [code]_process()[/code] function to make it script-wide. This allows us to use it in other functions too."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:85
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Then, replace the [code]4[/code] with [code]angular_speed[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:85
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "Using variables to store number values makes code easier to read. Tidy up this function by storing a value in a variable."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:85
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Define the [code]angular_speed[/code] variable at the top of the script to make it script-wide"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:85
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
#, fuzzy
msgid "Don't forget to use it in the [code]rotate()[/code] function"
msgstr "[code]_process()[/code] 함수를 예로 들어보겠습니다."

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:85
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "To define the variable, use [code]var angular_speed = 4[/code]"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:107
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Fixing an Out of Scope Error"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:107
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "There's something wrong with the code here. Can you see what it is?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:107
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Run the code and read the error."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:107
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Correct the code so it works as intended."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:107
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "Uh oh! There's something wrong here. Can you fix it?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-12-using-variables/lesson.bbcode:107
