#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:1
#. TRANSLATORS: Lesson header
msgid "Creating arrays"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:5
msgid "The [code]range()[/code] function we saw in the previous lesson outputs a list of numbers. For example, calling [code]range(3)[/code] produces the list of numbers [code][0, 1, 2][/code]."
msgstr "이전 수업에서 본 [code]range()[/code] 함수는 숫자 목록을 출력합니다. 예를 들어, [code]range(3)[/code]를 호출하면 [code][0, 1, 2][/code] 숫자 목록이 생성됩니다."

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:7
#. TRANSLATORS: The "term" in [glossary term="<term>"] should NOT be
#. translated here
msgid "A list of values, numbers or otherwise, has a precise name in code: we call it an [i][glossary term=\"array\"][/i]. So we can say calling the [code]range()[/code] function produces an [i]array[/i] of numbers."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:8
msgid "We could directly write and use that array inside our [code]for[/code] loop instead of the [code]range()[/code] function. You can run the next function step-by-step to see how it works."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:17
msgid "As you can see, the code still works the same. Notice that when we create a [code]for[/code] loop, we also create a local variable to which the loop assigns one value per iteration. Above, we named it [code]number[/code] because the array we loop over contains three numbers (0, 1, and 2)."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:18
msgid "But we could name it anything we'd like!"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:21
msgid "If we \"unroll\" the [code]for[/code] loop above, we'd get the following code with the exact same behaviour:"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:23
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "The syntax of arrays"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:27
msgid "We write arrays this way in GDScript."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:33
msgid "You start with an opening square bracket. Then, you write comma-separated values that compose the array. Finally, you need a closing square bracket to complete the array."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:34
msgid "Here are a couple of valid arrays. Notice how you can mix values, and how they don't need to follow one another."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:39
msgid "Because arrays themselves are a value type, just like numbers or [code]Vector2[/code], we can assign arrays to variables to reaccess them later."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:40
msgid "That'll come in handy in the next lesson, where we'll use those variables in loops."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:43
msgid "But first, let's see [i]when[/i] you'd use an array."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:43
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "When you use arrays"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:58
msgid "In computer programming, we use arrays [i]all the time[/i]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:59
msgid "Precisely, you'll use them whenever you need to store a [i]list of things[/i]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:60
msgid "You always need lists of things in games:"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:61
msgid ""
"- The player's party in an RPG.\n"
"- The items in the player's inventory.\n"
"- The high scores in an arcade game.\n"
"- The objects in the game world."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:62
msgid "All of those and many more rely on arrays."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:58
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Using arrays to follow a path"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:66
msgid "Let's look at a widespread use of arrays in games: finding and following a path."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:67
msgid "In games, you need allies or monsters to find their way to their target, whether it's the player or some point of interest."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:68
msgid "To achieve that, we use [i]pathfinding algorithms[/i]. As the name suggests, those algorithms find the path between two points and allow AIs to traverse the game."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:74
msgid "Many of those algorithms use arrays of [code]Vector2[/code] coordinates to represent the path."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:75
msgid "Take this turtle pet. It wants to follow the robot, but there are rocks in the way."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:76
msgid "How can we tell it where to walk to reach the robot? With an array!"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:82
msgid "Every value in the array is a [code]Vector2[/code] and represents a cell the turtle needs to walk through."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:83
msgid "Together, all the values in the array represent a path we can draw."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:88
msgid "In upcoming lessons, you will see how we can use arrays to store player inventories or design attack combos."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:89
msgid "For now, let's practice creating arrays."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:88
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Walking to the robot"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:88
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "The turtle wants to meet the robot! But it cannot find it on its own."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:88
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Fill the [code]turtle_path[/code] array with [code]Vector2[/code] coordinates indicating where the turtle should move to avoid the obstacles and arrive safely to the robot."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:88
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "The turtle can move up, down, left, or right. It cannot move diagonally."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:88
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "We recommend copying and pasting to fill the array with comma-separated [code]Vector2[/code] values quickly."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:88
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "Help the turtle find its way to the robot! Give it a path to follow to reach the robot."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:88
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Any path that doesn't touch rocks is valid. The turtle could first move down or to the right. So the first value could either be [code]Vector2(1, 0)[/code] or [code]Vector2(0, 1)[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:88
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Every [code]Vector2[/code] in the array should be one unit away from the previous one. That means there should only be a difference of 1 on the X-axis or the Y-axis between two [code]Vector2[/code] in the array."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:109
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Selecting units"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:109
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "In this tactical game, the player and computer can select multiple units at once. You need to call the [code]select_units()[/code] function and pass it an array of [code]Vector2[/code] coordinates to know which units to select."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:109
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Each [code]Vector2[/code] in the array represents a cell with a unit."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:109
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "You can pass arrays in function calls as arguments. As an array is a value type the computer recognizes, you can pass the whole array as a single function argument."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:109
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Select all units on the board by passing the correct array to the [code]select_units()[/code] function."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:109
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "Write an array to select all units on the board in this strategy game."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-19-creating-arrays/lesson.bbcode:109
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "You can write [code]Vector2[/code] values inside the brackets in the function call: [code]select_units([Vector2(1, 1), Vector2(3, 2), Vector2(3, 5)])[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:1
#. TRANSLATORS: Lesson header
msgid "Looping over arrays"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:5
msgid "We used the [code]range()[/code] function in combination with [code]for[/code] loops."
msgstr "우리는 [code]range()[/code] 함수를 [code]for[/code] 루프와 결합하여 사용했습니다."

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:13
msgid "The [code]range()[/code] function produced an array that the [code]for[/code] keyword could loop over."
msgstr "[code]range()[/code] 함수는 [code]for[/code] 키워드가 반복할 수 있는 배열을 생성했습니다."

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:14
msgid "We can give [code]for[/code] loops [i]any[/i] array, and they will loop over them just the same."
msgstr "우리는 [code]for[/code] 루프에 [i]어떤[/i] 배열이든 줄 수 있으며, 그러면 그것들을 동일하게 반복할 것입니다."

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:15
msgid "Instead of using the [code]range()[/code] function, we could manually write the numbers and get the same result."
msgstr "[code]range()[/code] 함수를 사용하는 대신, 숫자를 수동으로 작성하여 동일한 결과를 얻을 수 있습니다."

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:17
msgid "For each element inside the array, the [code]for[/code] loop extracts it, stores it in the temporary variable named [code]number[/code], and executes the loop's code once."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:18
#. TRANSLATORS: The "term" in [glossary term="<term>"] should NOT be
#. translated here
msgid "Inside the loop, you can access the [code]number[/code] variable, which changes on each [i][glossary term=\"iteration\"][/i]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:19
msgid "The code works regardless of the array or where you store it. Often, you will store arrays in variables for easy access."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:23
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz question
msgid "What will this code print?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:23
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "Compared to previous examples, we store the array in the [code]numbers[/code] variable. Using the [code]numbers[/code] variable in our [code]for[/code] loop allows the computer to access the array of numbers like before."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:23
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "We have three numbers in the array: [code]0[/code], [code]1[/code], and [code]2[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:23
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "The loop extracts each of them sequentially and assigns it to the [code]number[/code] temporary variable. As the loop processes each number, the output will print [code]0[/code], then [code]1[/code], then [code]2[/code], each on a separate line."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:23
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "0, 1, and 2"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:23
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "1, 2, and 3"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:23
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "0, 0, and 0"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:38
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Making the turtle walk, with a loop"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:42
msgid "In the previous lesson, you made a turtle walk along a path by writing [code]Vector2[/code] coordinates in an array."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:48
msgid "It's a [code]for[/code] loop that makes the turtle walk along the path."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:49
msgid "The loop works like this: for each coordinate in the array, it moves the turtle once to that cell."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:54
msgid "It's the same principle with unit selection."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:60
msgid "For each coordinate in an array named [code]selected_units[/code], we check if there is a unit in that cell. If so, we select it. "
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:61
msgid "In that case, we use an array, a loop, and a condition together."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:73
msgid "The code above uses several features you haven't learned yet:"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:74
msgid ""
"- In a condition, the [code]in[/code] keyword allows you to check if a value exists [i]in[/i] an array.\n"
"- The array's [code]append()[/code] function appends a new value at the end of the array."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:75
msgid "Notice the use of a period after the [code]selected_units[/code] variable, to call the [code]append()[/code] function. It's because this function exists only on arrays."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:76
msgid "When functions exist only on a specific value type, you write a dot after the value to call the function on it."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:77
msgid "We'll revisit those two features again in the following lessons."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:83
msgid "The beauty of loops is that they work regardless of the size of your arrays. "
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:84
msgid "The code just works whether you have one or ten thousand units to select. It is all accomplished with only a couple lines of code."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:85
msgid "That's the power of computer programming."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:86
msgid "In the following practices, you will use arrays combined with [code]for[/code] loops to achieve similar results."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:83
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Move the robot along the path"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:83
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Our AI pathfinding algorithm provided a path for the robot to move to the right edge of the grid. Your task is to use a [code]for[/code] loop to make the robot move."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:83
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "To move the robot, call [i]its[/i] [code]move_to()[/code] function, like so: [code]robot.move_to()[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:83
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "The [code]move_to()[/code] function only exists on the robot, which is why you need to access it this way."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:83
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "Our AI pathfinding algorithm is giving us a path to move the robot. Now, you need to make the turtle move along the path."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:83
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "You should start with a for loop that iterates over every cell in [code]robot_path[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:83
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "You need to pass the cell position to the robot's [code]move_to()[/code] function in the loop."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:106
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Back to the drawing board"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:106
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "We want to draw many rectangles, something surprisingly common in games."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:106
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "However, writing this code by hand can get tedious. Instead, you could store the size of your shapes in arrays and use a loop to draw them all in batches."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:106
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "That's what you'll do in this practice."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:106
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Use a [code]for[/code] loop to draw every rectangle in the [code]rectangle_sizes[/code] array with the [code]draw_rectangle()[/code] function."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:106
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "The rectangles shouldn't overlap or cross each other. To avoid that, you'll need to call the [code]jump()[/code] function."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:106
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "The drawing turtle makes its comeback. Fear not! Armed with loops, you'll make it draw faster than ever before."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:106
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Each value in the [code]rectangle_sizes[/code] array is a [code]Vector2[/code]. You'll need to access its [code]x[/code] and [code]y[/code] sub-components to draw rectangles."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:106
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "In the loop, you first need to call [code]draw_rectangle()[/code], and then [code]jump()[/code]. Otherwise, at least two rectangles will overlap."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-20-looping-over-arrays/lesson.bbcode:106
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "The arguments when calling [code]jump()[/code] can just be large enough to space out the rectangles. For example, [code]jump(300, 0)[/code]"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:1
#. TRANSLATORS: Lesson header
msgid "Strings"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:9
msgid "Throughout this course, we've mostly stored numbers in variables. But what if we wanted to store a player's name?"
msgstr "이 과정에서는 대부분 숫자를 변수에 저장했습니다. 하지만 플레이어의 이름을 저장하고 싶다면 어떻게 해야 할까요?"

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:10
msgid "This is where strings help us."
msgstr "이때 문자열이 도움이 됩니다."

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:11
msgid "Strings are instrumental in games and applications. We use them to display information such as the description of a spell or the name of a character."
msgstr "문자열은 게임과 애플리케이션에서 중요한 역할을 합니다. 주문 설명이나 캐릭터 이름과 같은 정보를 표시할 때 문자열을 사용합니다."

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:11
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "What are strings"
msgstr "문자열이란 무엇인가요"

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:19
msgid "A [code]String[/code] is a value type which holds text. To create a [code]String[/code], you write text wrapped in quotation marks ([code]\"\"[/code]). For example: [code]\"This is a text string.\"[/code]"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:20
msgid "The quotation marks differentiate strings from other value types and function names."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:21
msgid "You may remember we've used strings before in previous lessons."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:23
msgid "Under the hood, strings are arrays of characters. In fact, we can use a [code]for[/code] loop to loop through the characters of a [code]String[/code] as we would with any other array."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:25
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz question
msgid "Which of these are strings?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:25
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "[code]\"1\"[/code] and [code]\"name\"[/code] are strings."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:25
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "[code]\"1\"[/code] only contains a character and [i]doesn't[/i] represent the number [code]1[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:25
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "[code]\"name\"[/code] is made up of four different characters."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:25
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "\"1\""
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:25
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "\"name\""
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:36
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Why we use strings"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:48
msgid "Every piece of text you see in this app is a string that Godot is displaying for us."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:49
msgid "Much like how [code]Vector2[/code] variables make calculations easier, [code]string[/code] variables come with many helper functions and tricks we can use."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:50
msgid "We can use arrays to store strings too. This is useful for chaining animations. In this example, the [code]play_animation()[/code] plays a specific animation."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:52
msgid "In the next few practices, we'll use strings in combination with different concepts from earlier lessons."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:52
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Creating string variables"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:52
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Currently, the robot has a number stored in the [code]robot_name[/code] variable."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:52
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Change the [code]robot_name[/code] variable so that it's a string instead. You can give it any name you'd like."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:52
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "Give the robot a readable name using a string stored in a variable."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:52
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Strings need to be wrapped in quotes like \"Robi\"."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:52
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Replace the number 0 with your string (the robot's name)."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:73
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Using an array of strings to play a combo"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:73
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "In this practice, we'll chain together animations using an array of strings. You might find such combinations in fighting games."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:73
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "The robot has the following animation names:"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-21-strings/lesson.bbcode:73
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid ""
"- [code]\"jab\"[/code] (makes the robot perform a quick punch)\n"
"- [code]\"uppercut\"[/code] (the robot uses a powerful jumping punch)"
msgstr ""

